class Solution {
public:
    int minChanges(int n, int k) {
        if (n == k) return 0;
        int count = 0;
        while (n != k) {
            if ((n & k) == 0) return -1;
            n = n & k;
            count++;
        }
        return count;
    }
};
```

efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(log n)
space complexity: O(1)
energy implications: LOW
explanation: This solution uses bitwise operations to efficiently compare the bits of n and k. It iteratively clears the least significant bit that is set in both n and k, effectively reducing the number of bits that need to be changed. If a bit is cleared and the result is 0, it means that n and k have different bits in that position, so it's impossible to make n equal to k.

